The '''Tanimbar eclectus''',<ref>{{cite book |last=Steadman |first=David William |year=2006 |title=Extinction and Biogeography of Tropical Pacific Birds |publisher=University of Chicago Press |page=525 |isbn=0-226-77142-3}}</ref> or '''Riedel's eclectus'''<ref name="taylor">{{cite web |last1=Taylor |first1=Graham |title=Tanimbar Island Eclectus (Eclectus roratus riedeli) |date=12 May 2015 |url=https://eclectus-parrots.com/subspecies-info-tanimbar-island-eclectus/ |access-date=5 February 2023}}</ref> ('''''Eclectus riedeli''''') is a parrot species which is native to the [[Tanimbar Islands]]. It is smaller than the [[Moluccan eclectus]]. The male has a more bluish tinge to its green cheeks and neck, and its tail is edged with a broad band of yellow. The female has an all red plumage, except for royal blue primaries, yellow under-tail coverts and a broad band of yellow to edge the tail.<ref name=Forshaw78>{{cite book| author=Forshaw, Joseph M.| author-link=Joseph Forshaw| author2=Cooper, William T.| name-list-style=amp|year=1978| title=Parrots of the World| edition=2nd|publisher=Landsdowne Editions| location=Melbourne| isbn=0-7018-0690-7|pages=202–07}}</ref><ref name="taylor" />

==Aviculture==
Rare in captivity, the Tanimbar eclectus can be found in zoos and bird parks in Spain and Germany.<ref name="taylor" />

